rstand human behavior from an evolutionary perspective. To that end, The Hadza also articulates the necessary background for readers whose exposure to human evolutionary theory is minimal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHatsa (African people)xFood. 0aHatsa (African people)xHunting. 0aHatsa (African people)xSocial life and customs. 0aHunting and gathering societiesxTanzania. 0aHunting and gathering societieszTanzania. 0aSocial changexTanzania. 0aSocial changezTanzania. 0aSocial ecologyxTanzania. 0aSocial ecologyzTanzania. 0aSocial evolution. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520945449.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles